Too often people take on more responsibilities than required, which can hurt relationships (even though you were just trying to help the relationship) and hurt your mental health. If you’ve been finding yourself extra irritable or angry at others lately maybe it’s time to reevaluate what you are taking on and what you can let go of? If you’ve been feeling burnt out and depressed, maybe it’s time to release some responsibility that is not for you to carry?

You are responsible for your healing & happiness.

To truly unwire toxic people-pleasing from your brain, you will need to go back to the root of the issue first. Often people-pleasing can be traced back to childhood where you were taught that love only comes when you sacrifice yourself and the space. Maybe you had to play therapist? Or peacemaker? Maybe your parents pressured you to do well in a certain sport or activity to fulfill their dreams? 

Getting to the root is hard but rewarding work. In my new book Cleaning up Your Mental Mess I explain how to identify and rewire the root, and build healthy new thought patterns in 5 steps. It will be hard for those around you to understand what you are going through so they may either avoid you or try “fix” you as a coping mechanism. 

First of all understand it’s not your job to make people feel better or more comfortable at your own expense. Others never will fully understand and they should not try use understanding to be empathetic. 

What can help in these situations are the following:

1) let people know when you are having a bad mental health day. You don’t have to explain what is going on but just let them know you may need extra attention or extra space today. 

2) have grace for those around you because they may be trying their best to help or be there. Let them know what helps or doesn’t help if possible. 

3) talk to a therapist to get professional perspectives and advice. This is a game changer! 

At the end of the day you have to express, not suppress in order to heal. Do what you need to do for your mental health 💕

Listen to your body and your brain. If you are not in a good place mentally don’t try force change or force yourself to do more and be more. Rest! Rest is an essential part of recovery. Maybe it means cancelling plans for a bit, or going easy on working out, or eating your favorite comfort food. This feeling won’t last forever, and the sooner you embrace it and honor yourself, the sooner you will find yourself rested, recovered, and ready to continue doing the work.
